<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="640" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,219,921]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,418,441]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tsai &amp; Rédei" authorityYear="2015" box="[696,775,418,441]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Acanthosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pugnax">
<emphasis box="[696,775,418,441]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">pugnax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(m, f, n) ‘combative, fond of fighting’, referring to the produced, sharp humeri of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,219,921]" box="[113,803,482,505]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,239,482,505]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Unknown. The male 
<typeStatus box="[470,563,482,505]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected at light.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="640" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,219,921]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,257,514,537]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is apparently endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[652,733,514,537]" name="Taiwan" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
. Specimens are rare in collections, so far only the 
<typeStatus box="[274,367,546,569]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<specimenCount box="[420,557,546,569]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" type="generic" typeStatus="paratype">one paratype</specimenCount>
are known, both collected in the central, mountainous region of the main island of 
<collectingCountry box="[479,561,578,601]" name="Taiwan" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="640" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,219,921]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,224,610,633]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although the single male available is badly damaged (
<figureCitation box="[795,918,610,633]" captionStart="Figs 72–75" captionStartId="26.[151,188,1547,1566]" captionTargetBox="[194,1071,246,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-10@26.[151,1126,217,1516]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Figs 72–75. Acanthosoma pugnax sp. nov. 72–73 – male (holotype); 74–75 – female (paratype). Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303591" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303591/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">Figs 72–73</figureCitation>
), we judged that it, together with an obviously conspecific female, will make it possible to prepare a description which will allow unambiguous recognition of the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[113,1089,219,921]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">
The new species is taxonomically closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hsiao &amp; Liu, 1977" authorityName="Hsiao &amp; Liu" authorityYear="1977" box="[679,1018,706,729]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Acanthosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shensiense">
<emphasis box="[679,820,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">A. shensiense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="HSIAO T. Y. &amp; LIU S. L." box="[825,1018,706,729]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" pagination="300 - 302" refId="ref19524" refString="HSIAO T. Y. &amp; LIU S. L. 1977: Family Acanthosomatidae. Pp. 159 - 180, 300 - 302, plates 25 - 29. In: HSIAO T. Y., REN S. Z., ZHENG L. Y., JING H. L. &amp; LIU S. L.: A handbook for the determination of the Chinese Hemiptera-Heteroptera. Volume I. Science Press, Beijing, iii + 330 pp, 52 plates (in Chinese, English summary)." type="book chapter" year="1977">Hsiao &amp; Liu, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Liu, 1987)" baseAuthorityName="Liu" baseAuthorityYear="1987" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Acanthosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">A. montanum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LIU S. L." box="[237,339,738,761]" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" pagination="149 - 155" refId="ref20589" refString="LIU S. L. 1987: Acanthosomatidae. Pp. 149 - 155. In: HUANG F. S. (ed.): Forest insects of Yunnan. Yunnan Science and Technology Press, Kunming, 9 + 1622 pp, 16 plates (in Chinese)." type="book chapter" year="1987">Liu, 1987</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
as indicated by the presence of a sclerotized and pigmented longitudinal ridge along the dorsal rim of the genital capsule of the male (a potential synapomorphy) and the similar shape of the paramere. Regarding 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Liu" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[610,754,802,825]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Acanthosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montanum">
<emphasis box="[610,754,802,825]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">A. montanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the new species can be easily distinguished by the apically sharp humeri (apically obtuse, recurved in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Liu" baseAuthorityYear="1987" box="[890,1033,834,857]" class="Insecta" family="Acanthosomatidae" genus="Acanthosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="640" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montanum">
<emphasis box="[890,1033,834,857]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="640">A. montanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the different parameres, the more prominent posterior margin of laterotergites VIII of the female, and the reduced Pendergrast’s organs on ventrite VII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
